// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// two-column-paper.dok
// Testing: page(cols: 2) newspaper-style flow for research papers
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

doc(font: "Times New Roman", size: 10, spacing: tight) {

  header {
    center {
      italic(color: gray, size: 9) { "International Journal of Document Languages · Vol. 1, 2026" }
    }
  }

  footer {
    center {
      p { color(value: gray, size: 9) { "Page " } page-number }
    }
  }

  // ── Title section — full width, no columns ─────────────────
  page(margin: narrow, cols: 1) {

    space(size: 12)

    center {
      bold(size: 13) { "Dok: A Compact Document Language for AI-Generated Documents" }
      space(size: 6)
      p { "Mahmoud Ahmed" }
      italic(color: gray, size: 9) { "mahmoudxyz · GitHub" }
      space(size: 4)
      italic(color: gray, size: 9) { "Submitted March 2026" }
    }

    space(size: 12)

    // Abstract — full width
    box(fill: #F8F9FA, stroke: #CCCCCC) {
      bold { "Abstract — " }
      """
      We present Dok, a tree-structured document language designed as a compact
      compilation target for AI document generation. Unlike existing formats,
      Dok enforces a strict five-layer context inheritance model that eliminates
      ambiguity and reduces AI hallucination surface. A complete document
      compiles from fewer than 200 grammar tokens. We demonstrate that Dok
      produces correct RTL output for Arabic and Hebrew without manual XML
      manipulation, and show that the same source file compiles to DOCX, PDF,
      and HTML with identical structure. Dok is open source and available via pip.
      """
    }

    space(size: 6)

    p {
      bold { "Keywords: " }
      italic { "document generation, AI output formats, RTL support, OOXML, markup languages" }
    }

  }

  // ── Body — two columns ─────────────────────────────────────
  page(margin: narrow, cols: 2) {

    // 1. Introduction
    h2(size: 10) { "1. Introduction" }

    p {
      """
      Generating well-formatted documents programmatically
      has been a persistent challenge in software engineering.
      Existing approaches fall into three categories: low-level
      library manipulation (python-docx, reportlab), template
      engines (Carbone, Jinja2), and markup conversion (Markdown,
      LaTeX). Each carries significant drawbacks when used as an
      AI generation target.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      Low-level libraries expose implementation details that AI
      models hallucinate incorrectly. The OOXML element ordering
      required for correct RTL rendering, for example, is a
      frequent source of silent failures. Template engines require
      a separate template authoring step that couples document
      structure to application logic. Markup conversion loses
      formatting fidelity at the conversion boundary.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      We propose Dok, a document language designed from first
      principles as an AI compilation target. The core insight
      is that a document language for AI must optimize for three
      properties above all others: minimal grammar surface,
      unambiguous structure, and self-correcting error messages.
      """
    }

    // 2. Language Design
    h2(size: 10) { "2. Language Design" }

    h3(size: 10) { "2.1 The Five-Layer Model" }

    p {
      """
      Dok organizes every node into exactly one of five layers:
      document defaults, physical page, layout arrangement,
      text style, and content atoms. A node may only contain
      nodes from the same layer or layers below it. This
      constraint eliminates an entire class of structural errors
      that plague template-based approaches.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      Context flows inward through the tree. A child node
      inherits all properties of its ancestors without explicit
      declaration. This context inheritance model means that
      RTL direction, font family, and spacing presets set at
      an outer layer apply automatically to all content within,
      with no repetition required.
      """
    }

    h3(size: 10) { "2.2 Deliberate Omissions" }

    p {
      """
      Dok has no variables, loops, or conditional expressions.
      This is not a limitation — it is the primary design
      decision. Logic belongs in the host language. Dok's job
      is to describe document structure, not to compute it.
      This boundary makes AI output predictable: the model
      cannot produce arbitrarily complex Dok programs, only
      valid document descriptions.
      """
    }

    // 3. RTL Support
    h2(size: 10) { "3. RTL Support" }

    p {
      """
      Correct Arabic and Hebrew rendering in OOXML requires
      three XML elements in strict order inside the paragraph
      properties block: bidi, jc, and rPr. Incorrect ordering
      produces documents that render as left-aligned despite
      containing right-aligned text. This failure is silent —
      Word opens the file without error.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      Dok eliminates this class of errors entirely. The rtl
      layout node sets all required OOXML properties in the
      correct order at compile time. The author writes one
      wrapper node. The compiler owns the XML details.
      """
    }

    // 4. AI Integration
    h2(size: 10) { "4. AI Integration" }

    p {
      """
      The complete Dok grammar fits in approximately 200 tokens,
      making it practical to include in an AI system prompt.
      In our evaluation, Claude Sonnet 4 produced valid Dok
      output on 94% of first attempts when given the grammar
      as a system prompt, compared to 61% for equivalent
      python-docx code generation tasks.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      Validation errors in Dok include both source location
      and a corrective hint formatted for readability by both
      humans and language models. In a self-correction loop,
      the model receives the error, regenerates the failing
      section, and resubmits. Convergence to valid output
      occurs within two iterations in 98% of cases.
      """
    }

    // 5. Results
    h2(size: 10) { "5. Results" }

    p { "Table 1 summarizes output correctness across document types:" }

    table(border: true, striped: true) {
      tr {
        th { "Document Type" }
        th { "Valid %" }
        th { "RTL Correct" }
      }
      tr {
        td { "Invoice" }
        td { bold(color: green) { "97%" } }
        td { bold(color: green) { "Yes" } }
      }
      tr {
        td { "Report" }
        td { bold(color: green) { "94%" } }
        td { bold(color: green) { "Yes" } }
      }
      tr {
        td { "Legal doc" }
        td { bold(color: orange) { "89%" } }
        td { bold(color: green) { "Yes" } }
      }
      tr {
        td { "Mixed RTL" }
        td { bold(color: orange) { "91%" } }
        td { bold(color: green) { "Yes" } }
      }
    }

    space(size: 6)

    p {
      """
      All RTL documents rendered correctly in Microsoft Word
      2021 and LibreOffice 7.6. No manual post-processing
      was required in any test case.
      """
    }

    // 6. Conclusion
    h2(size: 10) { "6. Conclusion" }

    p {
      """
      Dok demonstrates that a compact, constrained document
      language significantly outperforms general-purpose code
      generation for AI document tasks. The five-layer model,
      combined with first-class RTL support and structured
      error messages, makes Dok a practical compilation target
      for production AI document pipelines.
      """
    }

    p {
      """
      Future work includes a DOCX-to-Dok decompiler to enable
      document editing workflows, and native PDF output to
      eliminate the LibreOffice dependency for print use cases.
      """
    }

    // References
    h2(size: 10) { "References" }

    p(spacing: compact) {
      "[1] "
      italic { "ECMA-376: Office Open XML File Formats." }
      " ECMA International, 5th ed., 2016."
    }

    p(spacing: compact) {
      "[2] MacSween, A. "
      italic { "python-docx: Create and update Microsoft Word .docx files." }
      " GitHub, 2013–2026."
    }

    p(spacing: compact) {
      "[3] Ahmed, M. "
      italic { "dok: A document language." }
      " github.com/mahmoudxyz/dok, 2026."
    }

    p(spacing: compact) {
      "[4] "
      italic { "Anthropic Claude API Documentation." }
      " Anthropic, 2026."
    }

  }
}
